. Introduction . Data Wrangling . Exploratory Data Analysis . Conclusion

Introduction This project entails the investigation of a dataset taken from the Movie Database(TMDb), "a community built movie and TV database "(https://www.kaggle.com/tmdb/tmdb-movie-metadata). Apiece row links to a movie and includes a range of data about each film.Pertinent data to be used in the subsequent analysis include the following variables: . original_tile . genres . release_date . release_year

In this report, I explore the following question . What Year has higest release of movies? . What Movie is with highest and lowest profit? . Which is Highest Budget movie and Lowest Budget Movies? . What Movies generated Highest Revenue and Lowest Revenue? . Which is Longest Runtime Movie and Shortest Runtime Movie? . Which is Highest Rated movie and Lowest Rated Movie? . Which Year has Highest Profit Rate? . what Movie duration liked by customers based on popularity? . Which is Year by Year Average Runtime of Movies? . What relationship can be established between variables such as revenue,popularity,budget,runtime and profit? . Which Movie Genre has the Highest Release? . Can we provide the list of most popular genres from year to year? . Can we provide the list of top 20 directors that direct maximum movies?

Throughout my analysis, profit(as calculated by subtracting each film's budget from its revenue) will be the dependent variable,while release year, release date , budget, and genre will be the independent variables.

ii. What Movie is with highest and lowest profit



















In [17]:



     


# compute the profit per movie
# create 'Profit' as a new column in the DataFrame
df4['Profit'] = df4['revenue'] - df4['budget']



     



















In [18]:



     


# use 'idmin' function to discover the index for movie with Lowest Profit
# use 'idmax' function to discover the index for movie with Highest Profit
# print row linked to the index
def find_minmax(x):
    # use 'idmin' function to discover the index for movie with Lowest Profit
    min_index = df4[x].idxmin()
    # use 'idmax' function to discover the index for movie with Highest Profit
    high_index = df4[x].idxmax()
    high = pd.DataFrame(df4.loc[high_index,:])
    low = pd.DataFrame(df4.loc[min_index,:])
    
    # print high profit movie and low profit movie
    print("movie with Highest"+x+":",df4['original_title'][high_index])
    print("movie with Lowest"+x+":",df4['original_title'][min_index])
    return pd.concat([high,low],axis = 1)

# call the find_minmax function.
find_minmax('Profit')

# generate a plot that has highest profit for top 5 movies

# generate a function to split string and each genre count is return
def count_genre(x):
    # concatenate all the genre rows
    data_plot = df4[x].str.cat(sep = '|')
    data = pd.Series(data_plot.split('|'))
    # each genre is counted and return
    info = data.value_counts(ascending=False)
    return info

# make the function for genre of each movie
total_genre_movies = count_genre('genres')
# plot bar using plot function 'genre Vs number of movies'
total_genre_movies.plot(kind='bar',figsize = (12,5),fontsize=11,colormap='tab20c')

# setup labels and title of plot
plt.xlabel('Number of Movies',fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Genre',fontsize=12)
plt.title("Genre With Highest Release",fontsize=14)
sns.set_style("darkgrid")



     






















    
    



































The bar chart above point to the fact that the Genre 'Drama' has the highest release of movies with 4790 while Comedy is second at 3794 and Thriller at 2908























xi.Can we provide the list of most popular genres from year to year



















In [36]:



     


# map entire rows of genre in a list
genre_details = list(map(str,(df4['genres'])))
genre = ['Adventure','Science Fiction','Fantasy','Crime','Western','Family','nan','Animation','War','Mystery','Romance','TV Movie','Action','Thriller','Comedy','Drama','Foreign','History','Music','Romance','Horror','Documentary']

# create a numpy array of year and popularity which contain entire rows of release_year and popularity columns
year = np.array(df4['release_year'])
popularity = np.array(df4['popularity'])

# create null dataframe whose columns are years and index are genres
popularity_df = pd.DataFrame(index = genre, columns = range(1960,2016))
# convert entire values of the dataframe from NAN to zero
popularity_df = popularity_df.fillna(value=0.0)

z = 0
for i in genre_details:
    split_genre = list(map(str,i.split('|')))
    popularity_df.loc[split_genre, year[z]] = popularity_df.loc[split_genre, year[z]] + popularity[z]
    z+=1



     



















In [37]:



     


# for precise results, compute standard deviation
def calculate_std(x):
    return (x-x.mean())/x.std(ddof=0)

popular_genre = calculate_std(popularity_df)

Conclusions:


In the first section I examined the year with the highest release of movies. I made my analysis based on the values of 'release_year' and number of movies. I was able to establish the fact that the number of year with the highest release of movies turned out to be 2014 with 700 movies.


Further more, I analyzed the popularity of movies based on runtime and found out that movies with average runtime of 100min had the highest popularity as compared to the ones with runtime of over 125min.


Limitation:


1.There is no normalization or exchange rate or currency conversion is considered in the course of this examination thus my analysis is limited to numerical values of revenue
2.During the data cleaning process, I split the data separated by "|" into list for analysis during the data exploration stage. This increased the time taken for computing the results.
3.Dropping missing or Null values from variables of my interest might skew my analysis and could skew inadvertent bias toward the relationship being analyzed etc.
